l fascia","Obturator internus","Urogenital diaphragm"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Epelvic diaphragm\u003C/strong\u003E is a muscular sling that forms the floor of the pelvic cavity. It comprises the levator ani muscle complex and coccygeus muscles bilaterally, which together create a bowl-shaped muscular sheet that supports the pelvic organs and maintains continence.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eperineal membrane\u003C/strong\u003E is a dense fascial layer in the anterior perineum that lies below the pelvic floor. The \u003Cstrong\u003Edeep perineal fascia\u003C/strong\u003E is connective tissue that invests the perineal muscles but is not the main supportive structure. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eobturator internus\u003C/strong\u003E contributes to hip movement and lines the lateral pelvic wall. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eurogenital diaphragm\u003C/strong\u003E is no longer considered anatomically accurate terminology.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe pelvic diaphragm is crucial for providing support to pelvic organs and maintaining their position. It has specialised gaps that allow passage of the urethra, vagina (in women), and anal canal.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The pelvic diaphragm consists of paired levator ani and coccygeus muscles that support pelvic organs.","The muscular pelvic floor divides the pelvic cavity superiorly from the perineal region inferiorly."],"references":["Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. Oxford University Press.","Padubidri, V. G., \u0026 Daftary, S. N. (Eds.). (2014). Shaw\u0027s Textbook of Gynecology E-book. Elsevier health sciences.","Raizada V, Mittal RK. Pelvic floor anatomy and applied physiology. Gastroenterol Clin North Am. 2008 Sep;37(3):493-509, vii. doi: 10.1016/j.gtc.2008.06.003. PMID: 18793993; PMCID: PMC2617789."]},"relationsh